The '''Center for Health and Health Care in Schools (CHHCS)''', located within the [[George Washington University School of Public Health and Health Services]], is a nonpartisan policy analysis and program-development research center that builds on a 25-year history of testing strategies to strengthen school-connected health care delivery systems for children and adolescents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sphhs.gwumc.edu/departments/preventioncommunityhealth/centerforhealthandhealthcareinschools |title=The Center for Health and Health Care in Schools. |publisher=The George Washington University |date= |accessdate=2012-02-08}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.healthfinder.gov/orgs/hr3594.htm |title=The Center for Health and Health Care in Schools: CHHCS |publisher=The Department of Health and Human Services |date= |accessdate=2012-02-13}}</ref>

==History==
Since the early 1980s, in collaboration with the [[Robert Wood Johnson Foundation]] and other partners, CHHCS has developed model interventions and technical assistance resources to support the development of school-connected prevention and care programs for students in [[K–12]] schools.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rwjf.org/pr/product.jsp?id=26253|title=The Center for Health and Health Care in Schools: An RWJF National Program |publisher=Robert Wood Johnson Foundation |date= |accessdate=2012-02-08}}</ref> In its earlier work CHHCS was known as the School-Based Adolescent Health Care Program National Program Office (1987–1992) and the Making the Grade National Program Office (1993–2000).<ref>Brodeur, P. (2002). School-based health clinics. In S.I. Isaacs & J.R. Knickman (Eds.), ''To improve health and health care. Vol III.'' San Francisco, CA: Jossey-Bass. Retrieved January 28, 2012 from http://www.rwjf.org/files/publications/books/2000/chapter_01.html</ref>

==Mission==
CHHCS’s mission is to strengthen the [[well-being]] of children and youth through effective health programs and services in schools. In addition to developing new models for school-connected programs, CHHCS explores organizational and financing challenges associated with taking programs to scale.

==Research Interests==
'''School-based Health Centers:''' [[Quality improvement]] and financing strategies to sustain and expand [[School-Based Health Centers]],<ref>Lear, J.G. (2007). Health at school: A hidden health care system emerges from the shadows. ''Health Affairs, 26,'' 409-419.</ref> in addition to providing practical resources to school-based health centers directly.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.seattleschoolbasedhealthcenters.org/?p=28|title=Center for Health and Health Care in Schools |publisher=Seattle School Based Health Centers |date= |accessdate=2012-02-15}}</ref>

'''School Behavioral and Mental Health:''' Program development, sustainability and quality improvement; associations between [[social emotional learning]] and education success.

'''School Health-Education Partnerships:''' Identifying strategies to build support at the state and federal levels for [[early intervention]] programs at school.

'''School Health Services and Health Care Reform:''' Examining the role of school health programs in a [[universal health care]] environment.<ref>Lear, J.G., Barnwell, E. A., & Behrens, D. (2008). Health-care reform and school-based health care. ''Public Health Reports, 123,'' 704-708.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2011/nov/28/local/la-me-school-health-20111128|title=Taking healthcare to students: Clinics at schools are becoming a key part of the nation's medical safety net. |publisher=Los Angeles Times |date= |accessdate=2012-02-16}}</ref>

'''School Nursing:''' Role in management of [[chronically ill]] children.

'''Children’s Oral Health:''' Developing school-connected preventive and treatment services for underserved populations.

'''Vulnerable Populations:''' Increasing access to care through school health programs for high need populations, including children from [[low-income]] families, [[immigrant]] and [[refugee]] children, and children from communities burdened by health and other disparities.<ref>DeAngelis, T. (2010). Found in translation. ''American Psychological Association, 41,'' 52.</ref>

==Consulting==
CHHCS provides technical assistance and other analytical services to a variety of public and private agencies in support of continued development of school-based health programs. Projects include advising state foundations on challenges and opportunities for school-based health centers under [[health care reform]], technical assistance to schools across the country in the support of school-based health centers or initiatives,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.edweek.org/ew/articles/2011/12/07/13lowe_ep.h31.html|title=To Boost Learning, Start With Emotional Health |publisher=Education Week |date= |accessdate=2012-02-15}}</ref> and assessing options for expanding [[school nurse]] programs. CHHCS has also been a part of the process for assessing financial and state policy data on school-based health centers across the country.<ref>Schlitt, J.J., Juszczak, L. J, & Eichner, N. H. (2008). Current status of state policies that support school-based health centers. ''Public Health Reports, 123,'' 731-738.</ref>

==Publications==
CHHCS research papers are published in peer-reviewed journals as well as posted as reports to the CHHCS web site.<ref>Behrens, D. & Lear, J.G. (2011). Strengthening children's oral health: Views from the field. ''Health Affairs, 30,'' 2208-2213.</ref> The Weekly Insider, provides information on grant opportunities, school health news, resources, and upcoming meetings.

==Current Initiatives==
Social-emotional learning at school and the intersection between state and federal policies and local programs; children’s oral health and options for school-based care;  health care reform and school-based care; chronic-[[disease management]] and [[school health services]].

